doc.ContractDescription: WE PROPOSE TO USE THE RECENTLY AVAILABLE WEALTH OF INFRARED DATA FROM SPITZER, HERSCHEL, AND WISE TO PERFORM A STUDY OF STAR FORMATION IN THE OUTER GALAXY. THERE HAVE BEEN MANY OBSERVATIONAL STUDIES OF STAR FORMATION IN REGIONS IN THE SOLAR NEIGHBORHOOD, AND MASSIVE REGIONS IN THE INNER PARTS OF THE GALAXY. HOWEVER, THE OUTER GALAXY, WHICH IS INTERMEDIATE IN METALLICITY BETWEEN THE INNER GALACTIC DISK AND THE MAGELLANIC CLOUDS, AND AT MUCH LOWER VOLUME DENSITIES, HAS NOT BEEN AS EXTENSIVELY STUDIED. THE EXTENSION OF THE SPITZER AND HERSCHEL GALACTIC SURVEYS TO THE OUTER GALAXY HAS NOW MADE THIS POSSIBLE. WE WILL USE TECHNIQUES DEVELOPED IN STUDIES OF NEARBY STAR FORMATION AND MASSIVE REGIONS SUCH AS CYGNUS X TO LOCATE YOUNG STELLAR OBJECTS IN THE OUTER GALAXY, USE MODEL FITTING TO DETERMINE THEIR PROPERTIES SUCH AS LUMINOSITY AND MASS, AND STUDY THEIR CLUSTERING PROPERTIES. COMPARING THE RESULTS TO STAR FORMATION REGIONS IN OTHER PARTS OF THE GALAXY WILL PROVIDE INFORMATION ON HOW DYNAMICAL PROCESSES CAN AFFECT THE MECHANISMS THAT INFLUENCE THE FRAGMENTATION OF MOLECULAR CLOUDS AND STAR FORMATION EFFICIENCY. THE RESULTS WILL HAVE APPLICATIONS TO THE STUDY OF STAR FORMATION IN OTHER GALAXIES, WHERE GLOBAL PROPERTIES CAN BE OBSERVED BUT WE CANNOT RESOLVE INDIVIDUAL CLUSTERS OR STARS IN THE INFRARED. THIS STUDY WILL PROVIDE A DATABASE OF OUTER GALAXY STAR FORMATION WHICH CAN BE USED TO SELECT OBJECTS TO FOLLOW UP WITH JWST.

doc.ContractDescription: MARS HAS THE MOST UNUSUAL MAGNETIC ENVIRONMENT IN THE SOLAR SYSTEM, AND OBSERVATIONS HAVE ESTABLISHED THAT THE MAGNETIC FIELD CONDITIONS STRONGLY INFLUENCE IONOSPHERIC BEHAVIOR: PEAK IONOSPHERIC ELECTRON DENSITIES ARE MUCH LARGER THAN NORMAL IN REGIONS OF STRONG AND VERTICAL MAGNETIC FIELD. THESE STRIKING RESULTS PROMPT TWO SIMPLE QUESTIONS THAT, STRANGELY, HAVE NOT YET BEEN ADDRESSED. WHAT IS THE SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION OF PLASMA IN REGIONS OF STRONG CRUSTAL FIELD? WHY DOES THE IONOSPHERE BEHAVE ATYPICALLY IN REGIONS OF STRONG CRUSTAL FIELD? INSPIRED BY THESE QUESTIONS, THE THREE OBJECTIVES OF THIS PROPOSAL ARE: 1. TO USE MARSIS DATA TO MAP THE STRUCTURE OF THE IONOSPHERE IN STRONGLY MAGNETIZED REGIONS OF MARS, THEN TO INVESTIGATE OBSERVED TRENDS. 2. TO USE THESE ELECTRON DENSITY MAPS TO EXPLAIN SEVERAL UNUSUAL OBSERVATIONS OF IONOSPHERIC CONDITIONS IN STRONGLY MAGNETIZED REGIONS. 3. TO USE NUMERICAL SIMULATIONS TO REPRODUCE THE STRUCTURE OF THE IONOSPHERE IN STRONGLY MAGNETIZED REGIONS OF MARS, THEREBY IDENTIFYING THE CRITICAL PHYSICAL PROCESSES. THESE OBJECTIVES WILL BE ACCOMPLISHED BY THE ANALYSIS OF ELECTRON DENSITY MEASUREMENTS BY THE MARSIS TOPSIDE RADAR SOUNDER, WITH THE SUPPORT OF NUMERICAL MODELS. IN TASK A, WE SHALL USE EXISTING TOOLS TO PROCESS MARSIS IONOGRAMS AND ASSEMBLE MANY TWO-DIMENSIONAL SLICES OF ELECTRON DENSITY AS A FUNCTION OF ALTITUDE AND LATITUDE OVER STRONGLY MAGNETIZED REGIONS. WE SHALL THEN ANALYZE THESE ELECTRON DENSITY SLICES TO MAP HOW THE SPATIAL DISTRIBUTION OF PLASMA IN THE IONOSPHERE IS AFFECTED BY THE LOCAL MAGNETIC FIELD CONDITIONS, AND EXPLORE HOW THE RESULTS ARE AFFECTED BY CHANGES IN SOLAR ZENITH ANGLE AND SOLAR WIND CONDITIONS. IN TASK B, WE SHALL TEST WHETHER THE TWO-DIMENSIONAL SLICES OF ELECTRON DENSITY PRODUCED IN TASK A ARE (1) CONSISTENT WITH EXPLANATIONS PROPOSED FOR MARSIS OBLIQUE ECHOES IN WHICH THE IONOSPHERE BULGES UPWARDS WHERE THE MAGNETIC FIELD IS STRONG AND VERTICAL, AND (2) CONSISTENT WITH RADIO OCCULTATION OBSERVATIONS OF NARROW LAYERS OF PLASMA IN STRONGLY MAGNETIZED REGIONS. IN TASK C, WE SHALL CONDUCT NUMERICAL SIMULATIONS WITH PHYSICS-BASED MODELS TO TEST THE HYPOTHESIS THAT FOCUSING OF PRECIPITATING MAGNETOSPHERIC ELECTRONS INTO MAGNETIC CUSPS, AND ASSOCIATED IONIZATION AND PLASMA HEATING, IS THE CAUSE OF THE ENHANCED PLASMA DENSITIES SEEN IN THESE REGIONS.

doc.ContractDescription: FORM NRESS-300 VERSION 3.0 APR 09 PI NAME : RANGA MYNENI ORGANIZATION NAME : BOSTON UNIVERSITY NASA PROPOSAL NUMBER 13-TERAQEA13-0002 PROPOSAL TITLE : MAINTENANCE AND EVALUATION OF COLLECTION 6 TERRA AND AQUA MODIS LAI/FPAR PRODUCTS SECTION VII - PROJECT SUMMARY THE OBJECTIVES OF THIS SUCCESSOR MODERATE RESOLUTION IMAGING SPECTRORADIOMETER (MODIS) (AND NEW LAND) SCIENCE TEAM MEMBER PROPOSAL ARE: (1) EVALUATION OF COLLECTION 6 (C6) TERRA AND AQUA MODIS LEAF AREA INDEX (LAI) AND FRACTION VEGETATION ABSORBED PHOTOSYNTHETICALLY ACTIVE RADIATION (FPAR) PRODUCTS - I.E. (A) ASSESSING/IMPROVING THE RETRIEVAL RATE OF THE MAIN RADIATIVE TRANSFER ALGORITHM GLOBALLY, (B) TESTING FOR CONSISTENCY BETWEEN C5 AND C6 PRODUCTS, (C) ASSESSMENT OF PRODUCT PRECISION, ACCURACY AND UNCERTAINTY, AND (D) INTERCOMPARISON WITH OTHER MODERATE RESOLUTION SATELLITE PRODUCTS. (2) MAINTENANCE OF C6 MODIS LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS - I.E. (A) CONTINUAL QUALITY ASSESSMENT AND MODIS INHOUSE PROJECT SUPPORT, (B) COMMUNITY SUPPORT AND OUTREACH, AND (C) UPDATING OF DOCUMENTATION AND DEVELOPMENT/DISTRIBUTION TO THE COMMUNITY FOR ENHANCING USER-FRIENDLINESS. (3) SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH WITH C6 LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS AND PUBLICATION OF JOURNAL ARTICLES. THE MOTIVATION AND JUSTIFICATION IS BASED ON TWO FACTS: (1) MODIS LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS HAVE A LARGE USER BASE. (2) C6 MODIS LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS WILL BE AT A SPATIAL RESOLUTION OF 500M AS OPPOSED TO ALL PREVIOUS COLLECTIONS, WHICH WERE AT 1KM RESOLUTION. THIS IS A SIGNIFICANT CHANGE FOR THE FOLLOWING REASONS: (A) THE SURFACE REFLECTANCES INPUT TO THE LAI/FPAR ALGORITHM WILL NO LONGER BE THE WELL-CHARACTERIZED 1KM PRODUCT (MODAGAGG) BUT A NEW 500M PRODUCT CALLED "L2G-LITE", AND (B) THE 8 BIOME MAP INPUT TO THE LAI/FPAR ALGORITHM WILL ALSO BE A NEW 500M PRODUCT. MORE IMPORTANTLY, IT WILL NO LONGER BE A STATIC, I.E. TIME-INVARIANT, MAP BUT A NEW PRODUCT (TEMPORALLY CHANGING - EVERY THREE YEARS AS CURRENTLY PLANNED BUT THIS COULD CHANGE). (C) THESE NEW INPUT PRODUCTS REQUIRE VETTING. A LIMITED "SCIENCE TEST" REVEALED SIGNIFICANT DISCREPANCIES BETWEEN THE CURRENT COLLECTION 5 (C5) AND SUCCESSOR C6 LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS. THIS CLEARLY DEMONSTRATED THE NEED FOR HANDS-ON PI AND CO-I INVOLVEMENT IN THE EVALUATION AND MAINTENANCE OF C6 LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS. THE MAIN DELIVERABLES,6 TERRA AND AQUA MODIS LAI AND FPAR PRODUCTS (INSTRUMENT-SPECIFIC AND COMBINED) WITH PIXEL-LEVEL QUALITY FLAGS, ARE UNIQUE AND UNMATCHED 18 YEAR TIME SERIES AT 500M SPATIAL RESOLUTION (8 AND 4 TEMPORAL GRANULARITY) OF KNOWN ACCURACY, PRECISION AND UNCERTAINTY. THE PRODUCTS WILL BE USED IN A RANGE OF APPLICATIONS, FROM DROUGHT MONITORING TO HYDROLOGICAL, ECOLOGICAL, CLIMATE MODELING AND MORE RECENTLY IN ACTIVTIES SUPPORTING THE IPCC ASSESSMENT REPORTS. CONTINUED AVAILABILITY OF THESE PRODUCTS WITH SIMILAR OR BETTER ACCURACY AND OF LONGER TIME SPAN WILL UNDOUBTEDLY INCREASE THIS USER COMMUNITY, AND WILL AID NASA REDEEM ITS INVESTMENT BY FACILITATING RESEARCH BENEFICIAL TO MANKIND IN THE AREAS OF MONITORING GLOBAL VEGETATION DYNAMICS, MODELING OF CLIMATE, WATER AND CARBON CYCLES, CROP YIELDS AND IN IMPROVED FORECASTS OF WEATHER.
